On Wed, 5 Jan 2005 11:20:48 -0700, Mike Clark &lt;mike@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I try to arrange my test case classes around common text fixtures.  One
&gt; side effect of doing that is it gives me an extra layer of context (a
&gt; namespace) on top of the test method name.  So, given my limited
&gt; knowledge of your problem domain, I might have a test case like this:
&gt; 
&gt;    public class OneSalesOrderLineTest extends TestCase {
&gt; 
&gt;      public void setUp() {
&gt;        // fixture for one sales order line
&gt;      }
&gt; 
&gt;      public void testCreateMultipleCustomerPurchaseOrderEntries() {
&gt;      }
&gt; 
&gt;      public void testSomethingElseAboutOneSalesOrderLine() {
&gt;      }
&gt;    }

Close, except I don&#39;t make the mistake you&#39;ve (purposefully) made
here, including the &#39;multiple&#39; test with the &#39;oneLineItem&#39; test.

My test class in this case is called something like
&quot;SpecificClientMappingSupportTest&quot; where &#39;SpecificClient&#39; is the name
of one of our clients who has a bit of byzantine business logic that
must be supported by our system.  The tests all rely on fixtures that
configure the system to understand that it&#39;s reading data for this
client, and that create inputs that resemble those that would come
from other parts of the system for this client.

So, like you, I&#39;m reading the tests in this class, and I know I&#39;m in
the context of the StarbucksMapperSupport (Starbucks is not the real
name, just a name I can see from my window).

&gt; &gt; This particular example is partly about readability (you could infer a
&gt; &gt; lot of the information, possibly, from the method name) and part about
&gt; &gt; disambiguity.  There are other tests involving CustomerPurchaseOrders
&gt; &gt; and Sales Order Lines that are similar.
&gt; 
&gt; Does using a separate test case help with the ambiguity?

I&#39;m not sure what you mean here.  I&#39;m trying to disambiguate this
testcase with another testCase that is named similarly:

testMultipleCustomerPurchaseOrderEntriesForManySalesOrderLinesWithDuplicates();

That test too has commentary describing the situation.  That one has a
bug# as well, apparently I did it wrong at one point in time.

&gt; 
&gt; &gt; Most of the time, these comments are written before the test.  I guess
&gt; &gt; you could say I practice document-first test development.  I write a
&gt; &gt; sentence or two about what the test is going to do (or just a method
&gt; &gt; name if it suffices -- you&#39;re right that it often does) then I write
&gt; &gt; the test.
&gt; 
&gt; I often use that technique, as well.  By writing out prose, I find
&gt; words that I&#39;d like to use in the test method name.

True, and most often I do the same thing.  But there are cases where I
felt that the prose held more information than the method name I came
up with.  I&#39;d already written the prose, so I left it to guide me in
the implementation, and describe the situation to the maintainers.

&gt; 
&gt; &gt; Ultimately, why wouldn&#39;t you want to write actual sentences?  I like
&gt; &gt; Java a lot, but English was my first language.
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m not saying you should never write sentences.  However, if I can
&gt; convey the same meaning in a method name, I&#39;ll do that instead of
&gt; maintaining two separate pieces of information (the sentence and the
&gt; method name).

I think folks are overstating my intentions a bit:  I&#39;m *not* saying
that *all* tests need javadoc documentation, I&#39;m not even saying that
most of them do.  The only point I&#39;m making is that occasionally you
need it, and not shipping the javadoc (the original question) makes
that occasional-but-important information unavailable to whoever is
using the unit tests.

-Kevin Klinemeier
